/josh4trunks","html_url":"https://github.com/josh4trunks","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/received_events","type":"user","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2013-11-29t17:39:13z","updated_at":"2013-11-29t17:39:13z","body":"i guess the 'bug' (though it's more on http/1.1's side) is that the php_auth_user have no chance to be reset. if a browser has a saved credential for a hostname they will never be able to login to owncloud unless using the same user. it might be possible for this to be reset with http://logout@www.example.com/owncloud but needs to redirect to a page that asks for new credentials."},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/owncloud/core/issues/comments/29529634","html_url":"https://github.com/owncloud/core/issues/6131#issuecomment-29529634","issue_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/owncloud/core/issues/6131","id":29529634,"user":{"login":"josh4trunks","id":1018807,"avatar_url":"https://gravatar.com/avatar/666f87548f9ddefc126b7ca41428e2a8?d=https%3a%2f%2fidenticons.github.com%2fb8756954ac46c8146997871f0d0a7929.png&r=x","gravatar_id":"666f87548f9ddefc126b7ca41428e2a8","url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks","html_url":"https://github.com/josh4trunks","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/received_events","type":"user","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2013-11-29t17:44:22z","updated_at":"2013-11-29t17:44:22z","body":"basically if an application uses http authentication then it will ask for new http authentication when the wrong credentials are input.\r\nbut since owncloud doesn't use http basic authentication but respects the php variable usually set by them it has no ability to reset those credentials.\r\n\r\nthis only affects sites that host both owncloud and an application using http basic authentication on the same domain. i am looking into a workaround, though really the bug is in the browser/http spec =["},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/owncloud/core/issues/comments/29529823","html_url":"https://github.com/owncloud/core/issues/6131#issuecomment-29529823","issue_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/owncloud/core/issues/6131","id":29529823,"user":{"login":"karlitschek","id":867445,"avatar_url":"https://gravatar.com/avatar/87ce2b4531ee1a0c32b50e0d8f049224?d=https%3a%2f%2fidenticons.github.com%2f06e7098636caebfc9c30c9f52eb905df.png&r=x","gravatar_id":"87ce2b4531ee1a0c32b50e0d8f049224","url":"https://api.github.com/users/karlitschek","html_url":"https://github.com/karlitschek","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/karlitschek/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/karlitschek/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/karlitschek/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/karlitschek/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/karlitschek/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/karlitschek/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/karlitschek/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/karlitschek/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/karlitschek/received_events","type":"user","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2013-11-29t17:48:43z","updated_at":"2013-11-29t17:48:43z","body":"hmm. but it is mainly a browser/client problem that it \"caches\" the credentials and doesn't ask again. other tools like curl allow to send different credentials to different urls. "},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/owncloud/core/issues/comments/29529968","html_url":"https://github.com/owncloud/core/issues/6131#issuecomment-29529968","issue_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/owncloud/core/issues/6131","id":29529968,"user":{"login":"josh4trunks","id":1018807,"avatar_url":"https://gravatar.com/avatar/666f87548f9ddefc126b7ca41428e2a8?d=https%3a%2f%2fidenticons.github.com%2fb8756954ac46c8146997871f0d0a7929.png&r=x","gravatar_id":"666f87548f9ddefc126b7ca41428e2a8","url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks","html_url":"https://github.com/josh4trunks","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/josh4trunks/received_events","type":"user","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2013-11-29t17:52:09z","updated_at":"2013-11-29t18:28:50z","body":"yeah and unfortunately i don't think there is a clean way of getting around this.\r\nhttp://stackoverflow.com/questions/449788/http-authentication-logout-via-php\r\n\r\n hopefully http/2.0 fixes this but for now i'm gonna try to work around it\r\n\r\n**edit**\r\nfixed this by unsetting authentication for my owncloud subdirectory in nginx. then php doesn't have a chance to incorrectly set php_auth_user.\r\n``fastcgi_param http_authorization \"\";``\r\n\r\n**edit2**\r\nnevermind, like you mentioned this breaks webdav.. i'll look for a way to reask for credentials"}]